title: Add DynamicQuantizeLinear to DNNL EP
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.

enable dynamicquantizelinear operator in DNNL EP. This op is needed to increase operator coverage for quantized bert based models

additional changes:
  add debug log in EP for operator coverage. The logging is used to track operator coverage breakdown and debugging

  block gpu elementwise op with 5 dims or more. OneDNN has limited dimension support on GPU for elemenwise ops (relu,log,abs and etc). The change will make DNNL EP not claim capability to elementwise ops with 5 or more dimensions when in GPU build.

 support for scalar output. OneDNN's internal memory representation is limited to tensor. As dynamicquantizelinear outputs scalar, in order to allocate the correct output scalar data handle for onnxruntime, this change is needed.

Signed-off-by: Zhaoyang Wang <zhaoyang.wang@intel.com>


**Motivation and Context**

title: Avoid skipping some tests
body:
**Description**: After the ONNX update, some tests are getting skipped because they are using the opset version as -1 which prompts the OpTester to use the latest "known" opset while creating the test model. After the ONNX update, the latest "known" version for the ONNX domain is 16 wheras the "released" version is 15. These tests eventually get skipped because by default only the latest **released** opset is run in OpTester:;Run(). So, default the logic in the OpTester to use the latest released opset in case the test sets the opset version as -1. All tests run with this change and test coverage drop is avoided.

title: Update mechanism to check installed cpp extensions
body:
**Description**:
ORTModule requires cpp extensions to be installed. onnxruntime assumes they are compiled in a subfolder and import them from this location after they were compiled. This PR introduces changes to check if these extensions are installed as a reguler package in case they are not found in the expected subfolder.

**Motivation and Context**
The cpp extensions cannot be easily installed on Windows. due to long path name, a compilation error may happen. In that case, the fallback meachnism is to manually compile every cpp extension and to install them.

title: Make ORTModule serializable
body:
Models that make use of `torch.multiprocessing` or `python.multiprocessing` require the model to be serializable and deserializable. Currenlty `ORTModule` is not serializable because of some of some of its attributes.

This pull request makes `ORTModule` serializable by introducing methods ```__getstate__``` and ```__setstate__``` that drop and reconstruct non serializable/deserializable attributes respectively.

title: [build] Is the current behaviour of build.py --cmake_extra_defines intended?

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: contributions welcome
labels.description: lower priority issues for the core ORT teams

labels.name: build
labels.description: build issues; typically submitted using template

body:
Currently `--cmake_extra_defines` argument is defined with `nargs="+"`, default action, which means that invoking the `build.py` script like this:
```
build.py --cmake_extra_defines onnxruntime_BUILD_UNIT_TESTS=0 --cmake_extra_defines onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB
```

adds only `-Donnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB` to the CMake invocation, not both of them, because the value of `args.cmake_extra_defines` is just `['onnxruntime=PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB']` -- in other words, only the last `--cmake_extra_defines` applies, the earlier ones are silently discarded.

_Silently discarding flags is annoying for hopefully obvious reasons._

The proper way to pass multiple cmake args is instead `--cmake_extra_defines onnxruntime_BUILD_UNIT_TESTS=0 onnxruntime_PREFER_SYSTEM_LIB`.

-----------------

I wonder whether the intention wasn't instead to have `--cmake_extra_defines` defined with no nargs, but with `action="append"` instead. However, this would break older scripts that use `--cmake_extra_defines` properly, so I think the best option might be to have `action="append", nargs="+"` and then explicitly flatten the resulting list of lists for the actual list of cmake args.

This results in error messages like:

When testing operator benchmarking, found this line brings up to 100+ μs of overhead, after `run_forward`.
After changing the `for ... in` logic into `for i in range(*)`, this overhead is gone.

Test case: benchmarking for Tile

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30493312/140557158-72a5c614-a759-4b4f-82b0-8e317f60d7c3.png)

The nvtx markers are added at:

```python
    def extract_outputs_and_maybe_update_cache(self, forward_outputs, device):
        """Extract the user outputs from the forward outputs as torch tensor and update cache, if needed

        Args:
            forward_outputs (OrtValueVector): List of outputs returned by forward function
        """
        if not self.enabled:
            with nvtx.annotate('return tuple(*)', color='red'):
                return tuple(_utils._ortvalue_to_torch_tensor(forward_output, device) for forward_output in forward_outputs)
                # this change

```

def _ortvalue_to_torch_tensor(ortvalue, device):

    with nvtx.annotate('_torch_tensor_from_dl_pack', color='cyan'):
        return _torch_tensor_from_dl_pack(dlpack_tensor, ortvalue, device)

title: Use the same allocator following Pytorch
body: Pytorch has a few CUDA allocators. Per our nsys profiling result, Pytorch uses `CUDACachingAllocator` and ORT uses `THCCachingAllocator`. This PR makes ORT also using `CUDACachingAllocator`. To disable Pytorch's memory caching (aka BFCArena in ORT), run `export PYTORCH_NO_CUDA_MEMORY_CACHING=1` and then you will see (in most cases), memory reaches peak at the beginning of BW. To re-enabling memory caching, do `unset PYTORCH_NO_CUDA_MEMORY_CACHING`. NOTICE: without this PR, ORT's memory peak happens at the end of BW even if Pytorch memory caching is disabled, because `THCCachingAllocator` never releases memory.

**Description**: Opset 12 introduced an attribute `select_last_index` for `ArgMax` and `ArgMin` and support for this in the CUDA implementation was not added. We can still use the existing opset-11 kernel as long as the value of the added attribute is the default value (which is the most common case) since the existing implementation's logic conforms to the required behavior when the value of the attribute is the default value. 

Although the [CuDNN API](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/cudnn/api/index.html#cudnnReduceTensor) we use in our kernel doesn't explicitly talk about what happens in case duplicates are encountered while picking the max/min indices, testing seems to indicate that the implementation is "stable" (i.e.) relative ordering is preserved which conforms to the expected behavior when the attribute takes on the default value (select_last_index == 0). The added unit test keeps this tested.

Limiting this change to just `ArgMax` for now as that is what we see in a 1P model whose perf we are trying to improve.

**Motivation and Context**
Improve CUDA kernel coverage for a 1P model and hence improve its performance on CUDA

This PR added three features:

1. The default behavior is inserting a QDQ pair to one tensor and multiple nodes can share a QDQ pair as their inputs if needed. 
    In TRT, QDQ pair can’t be shared between nodes, so it will create dedicated QDQ pairs for each node.
    Add a new extra options DedicatedQDQPair = True/False : Default is False. When inserting QDQ pair, multiple nodes can share a single QDQ pair as their inputs. If True, it will create identical and dedicated QDQ pair for each node.

2. Add a new extra options OpTypesSupportPerChannelQuantization = list of op type : Default is []. List of op types that has per channel quantization support

3. Add a new extra options QDQChannelAxis = Integer. Default is 0. Channel axis for QDQ pair when per_channel is True.
